---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="MDpedia — What Is MDpedia? | MDRPedia"
    description="MDpedia is the colloquial name for MDRPedia in Western medical communities. Learn about the world's leading physician encyclopedia, also known as MDpedia in the Americas, Europe, and Australasia."
>
    <article class="disambig-page">
        <div class="container">
            <!-- Breadcrumb -->
            <nav class="disambig-breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
                <a href="/">MDRPedia</a> <span>/</span>
                <a href="/about">About</a> <span>/</span>
                <span aria-current="page">MDpedia</span>
            </nav>

            <!-- Hero -->
            <header class="disambig-hero">
                <span class="disambig-badge">Disambiguation</span>
                <h1>MDpedia</h1>
                <p class="disambig-subtitle">
                    The Western colloquial name for <strong>MDRPedia</strong> — The Physicians' Register.
                </p>
            </header>

            <!-- Infobox -->
            <aside class="disambig-infobox">
                <h4>At a Glance</h4>
                <dl>
                    <dt>Official Name</dt>
                    <dd><a href="/">MDRPedia</a></dd>
                    <dt>Colloquial Name</dt>
                    <dd>MDpedia</dd>
                    <dt>Used In</dt>
                    <dd>Americas, Europe, Australasia</dd>
                    <dt>Origin</dt>
                    <dd>"MD" (Doctor of Medicine) + "pedia" (encyclopedia)</dd>
                    <dt>Eastern Equivalent</dt>
                    <dd><a href="/about/drpedia">DRpedia</a></dd>
                    <dt>Website</dt>
                    <dd><a href="/">mdrpedia.com</a></dd>
                </dl>
            </aside>

            <!-- Main Content -->
            <section class="disambig-content">
                <h2>What is MDpedia?</h2>
                <p>
                    <strong>MDpedia</strong> is the informal name by which <a href="/">MDRPedia</a> is widely known
                    in Western medical circles. The name derives from <strong>MD</strong> (Doctor of Medicine),
                    the primary medical degree in the United States, Canada, and many European countries,
                    combined with <strong>-pedia</strong> (from "encyclopedia").
                </p>
                <p>
                    While the official platform name is MDRPedia, physicians, medical journalists, and
                    academic institutions across the West frequently use "MDpedia" as shorthand when
                    referencing the register in publications, conference proceedings, and clinical settings.
                </p>

                <h2>Why "MD" in the West?</h2>
                <p>
                    In Western medical systems, the <strong>MD (Medicinae Doctor)</strong> credential is the
                    standard qualification for physicians. Countries including the United States, Canada,
                    United Kingdom, Germany, France, and Australia use the MD designation as the primary
                    medical degree. This made "MDpedia" a natural shorthand — physicians see the "MD" prefix
                    and immediately associate it with their professional identity.
                </p>

                <h2>MDpedia and DRpedia: Same Register</h2>
                <p>
                    It is important to note that MDpedia and <a href="/about/drpedia">DRpedia</a> refer to
                    the same platform: <strong>MDRPedia</strong>. In Eastern medical communities — the Middle East,
                    South Asia, East Asia, and Africa — the platform is known as DRpedia, using the universal
                    "Dr." honorific. Both names are recognized and direct to the same verified physician database.
                </p>

                <h2>What MDRPedia Offers</h2>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li><a href="/doctors">Verified physician profiles</a> across 85+ countries</li>
                    <li><a href="/rankings">Impact-based rankings</a> using the proprietary MDR Score</li>
                    <li><a href="/specialty">Specialty directories</a> covering every medical discipline</li>
                    <li><a href="/institutions">Institutional profiles</a> for hospitals and research centers</li>
                    <li><a href="/ethical-doctors">Ethics verification</a> with a transparent seal system</li>
                    <li><a href="/clinical-trials">Clinical trial tracking</a> linked to physician profiles</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>How to Access</h2>
                <p>
                    Whether you search for "MDpedia," "MDRPedia," or "DRpedia," you will find the same register
                    at <a href="/">mdrpedia.com</a>. The platform is free, open-access, and licensed under
                    Creative Commons (CC BY-SA 4.0).
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- Related Links -->
            <nav class="disambig-related">
                <h3>Related Pages</h3>
                <div class="related-grid">
                    <a href="/about/drpedia" class="related-card">
                        <span class="related-label">Eastern Name</span>
                        <strong>DRpedia</strong>
                        <p>The colloquial name used in the Middle East, Asia, and Africa</p>
                    </a>
                    <a href="/about" class="related-card">
                        <span class="related-label">About</span>
                        <strong>About MDRPedia</strong>
                        <p>Our methodology, history, and the Impact Quotient system</p>
                    </a>
                    <a href="/brand" class="related-card">
                        <span class="related-label">Design</span>
                        <strong>Brand System</strong>
                        <p>Logo, typography, tier seals, and editorial principles</p>
                    </a>
                    <a href="/doctors" class="related-card">
                        <span class="related-label">Register</span>
                        <strong>Browse Profiles</strong>
                        <p>Search the verified register of physicians worldwide</p>
                    </a>
                </div>
            </nav>
        </div>
    </article>

    <!-- FAQ Schema for SEO -->
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is MDpedia?",
                "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "MDpedia is the colloquial name for MDRPedia, the world's first independently-verified encyclopedia of physicians. The name is widely used in Western medical communities across the Americas, Europe, and Australasia."
                }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Is MDpedia the same as DRpedia?",
                "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Yes. MDpedia and DRpedia both refer to MDRPedia (mdrpedia.com). MDpedia is the Western name (from 'MD'), while DRpedia is used in Eastern medical communities (from 'Dr.')."
                }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Is MDpedia the same as MDRPedia?",
                "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "Yes. MDpedia is the informal Western name for MDRPedia — The Physicians' Register. The official platform is MDRPedia at mdrpedia.com."
                }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Why is it called MDpedia?",
                "acceptedAnswer": {
                    "@type": "Answer",
                    "text": "The name MDpedia comes from 'MD' (Doctor of Medicine), the primary medical degree in Western countries, combined with '-pedia' (encyclopedia). Western physicians naturally shortened MDRPedia to MDpedia."
                }
            }
        ]
    })} />

    <!-- BreadcrumbList Schema -->
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [
            { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "MDRPedia", "item": "https://mdrpedia.com" },
            { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "About", "item": "https://mdrpedia.com/about" },
            { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "MDpedia", "item": "https://mdrpedia.com/about/mdpedia" }
        ]
    })} />
</Layout>

<style>
    .disambig-page { max-width: 860px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 20px 100px; }

    .disambig-breadcrumb {
        padding: 20px 0; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12px;
        color: var(--ink-3); letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    }
    .disambig-breadcrumb a { color: var(--ink-2); text-decoration: none; }
    .disambig-breadcrumb a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
    .disambig-breadcrumb span { margin: 0 6px; }

    .disambig-badge {
        display: inline-block; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 10px;
        letter-spacing: 0.18em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-blue);
        border: 1px solid var(--ink-blue); padding: 4px 10px; border-radius: var(--r-2);
        margin-bottom: 16px;
    }

    .disambig-hero { padding: 40px 0 32px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); }
    .disambig-hero h1 {
        font-family: var(--font-serif); font-size: 3.2rem; font-weight: 400;
        color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 12px;
    }
    .disambig-subtitle { font-size: 1.2rem; color: var(--ink-2); max-width: 50ch; }

    .disambig-infobox {
        float: right; width: 260px; margin: 32px 0 24px 32px;
        background: var(--paper-2); border: 1px solid var(--rule);
        border-radius: var(--r-3); padding: 20px;
    }
    .disambig-infobox h4 {
        font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.14em;
        text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-3); margin-bottom: 16px;
        padding-bottom: 8px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }
    .disambig-infobox dl { display: grid; gap: 8px; }
    .disambig-infobox dt {
        font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.1em;
        text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-3);
    }
    .disambig-infobox dd {
        font-size: 14px; color: var(--ink); margin: 0 0 8px;
        padding-bottom: 8px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }
    .disambig-infobox dd:last-child { border-bottom: none; padding-bottom: 0; margin-bottom: 0; }
    .disambig-infobox a { color: var(--ink-blue); text-decoration: underline; }

    .disambig-content { padding-top: 32px; }
    .disambig-content h2 {
        font-family: var(--font-serif); font-size: 1.6rem; font-weight: 400;
        color: var(--ink); margin: 2rem 0 0.8rem; padding-top: 1rem;
        border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    }
    .disambig-content h2:first-child { border-top: none; margin-top: 0; padding-top: 0; }
    .disambig-content p { font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--ink-2); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .disambig-content a { color: var(--ink-blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

    .feature-list {
        list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 1rem 0;
        display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 8px;
    }
    .feature-list li {
        padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--paper-2); border: 1px solid var(--rule);
        border-radius: var(--r-2); font-size: 14px;
    }
    .feature-list li a { color: var(--ink-blue); text-decoration: none; }
    .feature-list li a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .disambig-related {
        margin-top: 3rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 2px solid var(--rule);
        clear: both;
    }
    .disambig-related h3 {
        font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.18em;
        text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-3); margin-bottom: 16px;
    }
    .related-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px; }
    .related-card {
        padding: 20px; background: var(--paper-2); border: 1px solid var(--rule);
        border-radius: var(--r-3); text-decoration: none; color: var(--ink);
        transition: border-color var(--t-fast) var(--ease);
    }
    .related-card:hover { border-color: var(--ink-blue); }
    .related-label {
        display: block; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 10px;
        letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-3);
        margin-bottom: 4px;
    }
    .related-card strong { font-size: 15px; display: block; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .related-card p { font-size: 12px; color: var(--ink-3); margin: 0; }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .disambig-hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; }
        .disambig-infobox { float: none; width: 100%; margin: 24px 0; }
        .feature-list { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
        .related-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
</style>
